\chapter{uppercase{Appendix}}
\label{chap:appendix}
\section{Types of instructions}
\label{sec:type}
MIRA can handle the following type of instructions:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \label{itm:simple} Simple clear-cut imperatives (\cite{ChrisFox}), such as \textit{``Shut the door"}.
\item Negative imperatives (\cite{ChrisFox}), like \textit{``Don't come to the party"}.
\item Imperatives that denote a sequence \cite{Hare}, such as \textit{``Put on a parachute and jump out"}.
\item Imperatives that denote the condition or reason, like \textit{``If it is raining, take an umbrella"}.
\item Imperatives that indicate the goal, like \textit{``Exercise well to stay healthy"}.
\item Imperatives that indicate both reason and goal, like \textit{``Since grandmother is weak, take this piece of cake, to strengthen her"}.
\item Imperatives that occur with \textit{or}, like \textit{``To write, take the pen or pencil"}.
\item Imperatives that occur with \textit{and}, such as:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{``Shut the window and close the door"}.
\item \textit{``To write, take the pen and to draw, take the pencil"}.
\item \textit{``If it is raining, take an umbrella and wear a raincoat"}.
\item \textit{``If it is raining, take an umbrella and if it is not raining, don't take an umbrella"}.
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}
\newpage
%\chapter{Theorem proofs}
\section{Proof of theorem \ref{th:rimp}}
\label{sec:proofrip}
\begin{proof}
The theorem \\
``Let an imperative be given by $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi) \rightarrow_p \theta)$. It evaluates to $N$ if $\mathcal{E}(\theta) = \bot$; and evaluates to $S$ or $V$, if $\mathcal{E}(\theta) = \top$" can be proved using the task table. \\
\begin{table}[h]
\begin{center}
\caption{Evaluation of $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi) \rightarrow_p \theta$}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
$\tau$ & $\varphi$ & $\theta$ & $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi)$ & $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi) \rightarrow_p \theta$ \\
\hline
$\top$ & $S$ & $\top$ & $S$ & $S$ \\
\hline
$\top$ & $V$ & $\top$ & $V$ & $V$ \\
\hline
$\bot$ & $S$ & $\top$ & $N$ & $N$ \\
\hline
$\bot$ & $V$ & $\top$ & $N$ & $N$ \\
\hline
$\top$ & $S$ & $\bot$ & $S$ & $N$ \\
\hline
$\top$ & $V$ & $\bot$ & $V$ & $N$ \\
\hline
$\bot$ & $S$ & $\bot$ & $N$ & $N$ \\
\hline
$\bot$ & $V$ & $\bot$ & $N$ & $N$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\label{tab:rimp}
\end{center}
\end{table}
From the task table \ref{tab:rimp}, it can be seen that when $\theta = \bot$, $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi) \rightarrow_p \theta$ evaluates to $N$ and when $\tau = \theta = \top$, $(\tau \rightarrow_r \varphi) \rightarrow_p \theta$ evaluates to $S$ or $V$.\\
Hence the proof.
\end{proof}
